In most of the cases in Plautus and Terence in which a long syllable is scanned as a short syllable after a monosyllabic word, the monosyllabic word is either qnid (interrogative), a personal pronoun, sed, uel, or ut,—placed in approximate order of fre- quency.

ἓ 4. Plautus makes free use of synizesis and often treats i and u as consonants, thus fusing two syllables into one. This process is indicated throughout the text of this edition by italics. For (aruit, v. 2 cf. fuit passim and crepuit, Aul. 4. 5. 5. The converse process, of making iam a dissyllable after nunc, is found vv. 115, 767, 774.

ἓ 5. Syncope, or the suppression of a short vowel when it is between two consonants which can be conveniently pronounced together, is used in Plautus more freely than in Classical Latin; as alteri, altera pronounced altri, altra.
